title: For Sale:   Iver Johnson TP22
postcontent: The Iver Johnson TP22 is a clone of Bond's iconic pistol; the Walther PPK. The TP22 which is chambered in .22 Long Rifle and is a double action automatic, hammer safety, polished blue metal pocket hand gun. The TP22 is a dead ringer for the Walther PPK whose heritage goes back to 1928. The Iver Johnson TP22 breaks down exactly like a Walther PP, PPK, PPK/S. The TP22 was manufactured between 1982 and 1986, it is based on an Erma Werkes design and some of the earliest production used Erma parts. It is a sound design that has an internal firing pin block. When the manual external safety is applied the firing is blocked at both the front and rear. I use Remington .22 LR Thunderbolt ammo and have had no issues whatsoever during target practice. This is a small carry pocket pistol that when carried goes unnoticed. The handgun does show wear from holster carry but is in very-very good shape.  Price is FIRM.

Originally designed for the American market, the USP (Universal Self-loading Pistol) has found international acceptance as an accurate and ultra-reliable handgun. Features favored by U.S. law enforcement and military users provided much of the design criteria for the USP. All USPs use a fiber-reinforced polymer frame stiffened by stainless steel inserts at areas subject to stress and friction. HK pioneered this use of polymer materials in the production of handguns more than 30 years ago with the development of the VP70Z and P9S pistols.

The USP control lever, a combination safety and decocking lever, is frame mounted and quickly accessible, unlike the slide-mounted safeties common on many semi-automatic pistols.

Using a modified Browning-type action with a special patented recoil reduction system, the USP recoil reduction system reduces recoil effects on pistol components and also lowers the recoil forces felt by the shooter. This same recoil reduction system has been tested and proven in the HK Mark 23 pistol developed for the U.S. Special Operations Command. The USP recoil reduction system is insensitive to ammunition types and requires no special adjustment or maintenance. It functions effectively in all USP models.

The modular design of the USP's internal components allows the control lever function to be switched from the left to the right side of the pistol for left-handed shooters.

title: For Sale:  M1887 Husqvarna Swedish Nagant Revolver
postcontent:
Up for sale is an extremely rare cousin of the Russian gas-seal Nagant revolver. Just under 14,000 of these revolvers were made, compared to over 2 million of the Russian variety.

I originally interpreted the serial numbers as this pistol being made in 1899, however the serial list I was viewing didn't consider the couple hundred serialed revolvers that we not delivered to the army and instead were sold to civilians. This means this revolver is from 1898 and is considered an "antique." As an antique I can ship it right to your front door- no FFL, no paperwork.

This is a Swedish made M1887 double-action Revolver designed by Leon Nagant and manufactured by Husqvarna for their army. 

It shoots the 7.5mm Swedish Nagant cartridge and 7.5mm Swiss Ordinance cartridge interchangeably, so ammo is available for it online and through catalogs. It can also shoot the .32 S+W short and .32 S+W long wadcutters and lead ball ammo with a few bulged cases. NO FMJ's!!! These are very weak cartridges and won't harm the gun- accuracy also wont be as good as quality 7.5 ammo but for plinking out to 50 feet they are fine. These guns are also popular with reloaders as .32-20 cases can be reloaded with black powder and a .30 lead ball for a good plinking load.

Condition is overall at 75%+. Blueing is excellent on most parts. No rust or pitting. Bore is shiny with no pitting and strong cut rifling. Straw finished parts have gone to a patina-esqe finish but are still  glossy. 6 shot cylinder is excellent. Grips are original, have no cracks, and strong checkering- has never been refinished. Action is smooth and function is 100%. DA trigger pull is hefty, but smooth. SA trigger pull is very light and crisp without being unsafe. This is very high quality hand made craftsmanship here.

All #'s are matching on every part except the cylinder which is from a pistol one month older. The frame is also marked with a serial number that was added to the gun when it was re-issued in the 1940's for Landstormen (home guard) use.

There are conversions to turn these into .22 revolvers.

Own this fine Swedish revolver for $650 trade $500 cash in person $600 shipped (Paypal, postal money order, or personal/certified check only- check must clear before it is shipped)  Must be over 18 to purchase.

Prices are not negotiable.

Would trade for other guns. and certain calibers of ammo. I like old guns with historical meaning. I could use a beater browning auto 5 plus cash. A Luger, P38, or Browning Hi Power would be nice. What do you have?

title: For Trade:  Art of negotiations
postcontent:
Yes, it's an art... and it is lost on most of you. The idea is simple. I have an item. My goal is to get the best trade or most amount possible. You want an item. Your goal is to acquire the item at the cheapest possible price or least amount of trade. So you offer low, the seller then counter offers until you reach a happy medium, and the item exchanges hands. This is how negotiations work in the REAL world. 
Sadly, here on Armslist, negotiations are terribly misunderstood. Offers that come in lower than the seller wants are met with hostile trash talk. Conversely, if a seller is asking too much most people refuse to negotiate or make the counter offer. I can't tell you how many of you ignorant people I've dealt with on here that have no fucking idea how to communicate. You people suck. Your Glock isn't worth $600 because you had someone put night sights on it. Your Century AK isn't worth $1000 because you added a Tapco stock... And when I offer you less (actual value) your reply or COUNTER OFFER should be worded with respect, since we're both men. 
Last thing: just because some asshole on your television show advises you to think that your item is worth MORE in trade than it is in cash, doesn't make it so. Your used ass equipment is only worth what someone is willing to give for it. It's not worth more in trade because that's what the gays do on tv. Wake the fuck up and get with reality. Quit being so stupid and start communicating. Make offers, when you receive offers think about them and feel free to make a counter offer. This breakdown of communication is as disgusting as the spineless humans behind their keyboards spouting their trash talk and acting like children. Good day.

title: For Sale/Trade:  CZ-50
postcontent:
After the Second World War, Czechoslovakia's Ministry of the Interior requested a new pistol design from Česká zbrojovka Uherský Brod. The resulting gun was chambered in .32 ACP and designed by two brothers Jan and Jaroslav Kratochvíl. It combined elements from both the Walther PP and PPK. The pistol is fed from an 8-round single-stack magazine, located within the bakelite paneled grip. Small fixed sights are located on top of the slide. The pistol functions via the blowback principal - recoil causes the slide to move backwards, thereby compressing a spring around the fixed barrel. After it reaches the end of its rearward travel, the recoil spring returns the slide to its forward position, stripping and chambering a new round from the magazine as it does so, rendering the gun ready to fire again. Hammer and trigger operation is double-action - that is, the hammer can be cocked and released by a squeeze of the trigger.

This one is in very good condition ,no pitting in the barrel and the rifling is in good condition also, safety and decocker are functional. Comes with case, two mags, inside/outside holster. 25rds of ball

make me an offer.

title: For Sale:  Remington M1917 - Sgt. York Rifle
postcontent:
The M1917 was used by the US in WW1, most notably Sgt Alvin York.  The M1917 was made by three different companies: Remington, Eddystone, and Winchester.  

The rifle maintains the British cock-on-closing feature, in which the bolt's mainspring is loaded and the rifle cocked as part of the return stroke of the bolt, which aided rapid fire, especially as the action heated up. Most bolt action designs after the Mauser 98 cocked as part of the opening stroke. The rifle has a characteristic "belly" due to a deeper magazine, allowing the rifle to hold six rounds of the US .30-06 cartridge in the magazine, and one in the chamber. In a manufacturing change from the Mauser 98 and the derivative Springfield, the bolt is not equipped with a third 'safety' lug. Instead, as on the earlier Model 1895 (Chilean) Mauser, the bolt handle recesses into a notch in the receiver, which serves as an emergency locking lug in the event of failure of the frontal locking lugs. This change saved machine time needed on the rifle bolt, cutting costs and improving production rates, and this alteration has since been adopted by many commercial bolt action rifle designs for the same reasons. The location of the safety on the right rear of the receiver has also been copied by most sporting bolt action rifles since, as it falls easily under the firer's thumb. 

The M1917 is well-suited to the powerful, rimless .30-06 round. The M1917's barrel is a  5-groove left hand twist, in contrast to the 4-groove right hand twist rifling of the M1903 Springfield and other US designed arms.The M1917 had a long 26-inch heavyweight barrel compared to the lighter 24-inch barrel of the M1903 Springfield. With the longer sighting plane, the M1917 proved generally more accurate at long distances than the M1903.

This particular Remington M1917 has been enhanced with the addition of a more sporting stock, and has more accurate peep sights installed.  She is a great shooter, and capable of tight groups with modern ammo.  Bore and rifling in Ex condition, and she has had a trigger job in the past, give her a pretty good feel. The finish is 100%

The rifle is over 50 years and eligible for a face to face sale.  Cash only.

OK guys, I purchased this DOUBLE SET TRIGGER MANNLICHER from a collector's estate, and I had to REMOVE THE COSMOLINE from the barrel, action, and trigger!!!
